          <tr>
            <td width="35" height="222" rowspan="2">&nbsp;</td>
            <td width="535" colspan="3" align="left" valign="top">
			  <p align="justify">Robustness,  a fundamental and ubiquitous observed phenomenon in biological systems, is the  invariance of phenotypes in the face of various perturbations. Depending on  whether the perturbations are inheritable or not, the robustness is  characterized as genetic robustness or environmental robustness. Phenotype  robustness appears at various levels of biological organization, including gene  expression, protein folding, metabolic flux, physiological homeostasis,  development, and even organism fitness. Biologists have a long-standing interest in  robustness, going back to Fisher&rsquo;s work on dominance, and to Waddington&rsquo;s developmental canalization research. Despite the plethora of observations of  robustness in nature, to date, the evolutionary origins of robustness are far  less clear. Whether it evolves as a direct consequence of natural selection, as  an intrinsic property of adaptations, or as congruent correlate of environment  robustness, however, is still controversial. Addressing this challenge, a convenient computational package is strongly  needed to fully elucidate the evolutionary mechanisms of robustness. </p>
			  <p align="justify">Given  quantitative measure of structural robustness, in this study, we develop an open-source integrated system named EvoRSR  (<u>Evo</u>lution of <u>R</u>NA <u>S</u>tructural <u>R</u>obustness) to explore the  evolution of robustness based on the biologically important landscapes induced  by RNA folding. </p>
			  <p align="justify">EvoRSR is available as C source code and  compiled binaries for Unix and Linux. See <a href="download.html">download page</a>.</p>
			  <p align="justify">If you use EvoRSR in your own research,  please cite:<br>
		    Wenjie Shu, Xiaochen  Bo, Zhiqiang Zheng, Shengqi Wang. RSRE: RNA structural robustness evaluator. <em>Nucleic  Acids Res.</em>. 2007, 35,W314-W319.<br>
		    Wenjie Shu, Xiaochen  Bo, Zhiqiang Zheng, Shengqi Wang. EvoRSR:  an integrated system for exploring evolution of robustness. (submitted)</p></td>
          </tr>
